    "messageBody": "<div id=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889\">\n<html><head>\n \n<title>Message</title>\n\n</head> \n \n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Arial\" color=\"#0000ff\" size=\"2\">You \ncan call System.setOut to set destination for System.out.println. To capture all \noutput to System.out in a String write some code like this:</font></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Arial\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\"></font></span>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Courier New\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\">PrintStream saveOut = System.out;</font></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Courier New\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\">try {</font></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Courier New\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\">&nbsp; ByteArrayOutputStream baos = new \nByteArrayOutputStream();</font></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Courier New\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\">&nbsp; PrintStream&nbsp;ps = new PrintStream(baos);</font></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Courier New\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\">&nbsp; System.setOut(ps); // Set System.out to capture \noutput</font></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Courier New\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\">&nbsp; // Execute code that you are testing and that writes to \nSystem.out</font></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Courier New\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\">&nbsp; ps.flush();</font></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Courier New\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\">&nbsp; String capturedOutput = new \nString(baos.toByteArray());</font></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Courier New\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\">&nbsp; // Compare capturedOutput with the expected \nvalue</font></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Courier New\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\">}</font></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Courier New\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\">finally {</font></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Courier New\"><font color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\">&nbsp; System.setOut(saveOut); // Restore \nSystem.out</font></font></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Courier New\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\">}</font></span></div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Arial\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\"></font></span>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889776301400-29112001\"><font face=\"Arial\" color=\"#0000ff\"\n size=\"2\"></font></span>&nbsp;</div>\n<blockquote><span title=\"qreply\"> <blockquote\n style=\"PADDING-LEFT:5px;MARGIN-LEFT:5px;BORDER-LEFT:#0000ff 2px solid;MARGIN-RIGHT:0px;\">\n  <div></div>\n  <div class=\"ygrps-yiv-372046889OutlookMessageHeader\" lang=\"en-us\" dir=\"ltr\" align=\"left\"><font\n face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">-----Original Message-----<br><b>From:</b> Bob Koss \n  [mailto:koss@...] <br><b>Sent:</b> Wednesday, November 28, 2001 \n  4:51 PM<br><b>To:</b> junit@yahoogroups.com<br><b>Subject:</b> Re: [junit] \n  Capturing the standard out of a program that I&#39;m testing<br><br></font></div>\n  <blockquote>Does anyone have any examples of code that captures the standard \n    out of<br>a Java program.<br><br>I am trying to test a program that outputs \n    using<br>System.out.print/println and I want to capture this output within \n    my<br>test.<br><br></blockquote><br>You can declare a String variable and \n  examine it from your test that it has the correct value.<br><br>Pass this \n  string to println() and assume println() \n  works.<br><br><br> ---<br>Robert Koss, Ph.D. | Training, Mentoring, \n  Contract Development<br>Senior Consultant | Object Oriented Design, C++, \n  Java<br>www.objectmentor.com | Extreme \nProgramming<br></blockquote></span></blockquote></html> \n</div>", 
